description.value: Glazed composition figure of Bes; only head, cavetto moulding and Atef-crown survived. Miniature headspreserved on the right side, behind the ear. Petrie interprets these as two deities, Webb thinks they are monkeys. However, seems to represent the four sons of Horus (four miniature heads, not two). Very delicate modelling. Finely detailed features, eyes, curved wrinkles /eyebrows, neat nose and mouth, animal ear projects at right and beard below marked with incisions. Glaze gone, but greenish colouring survives. Core- buff , hard, fine to medium texture.

description.value: Gold amuletic figure of Thoth holding wedjat-eye.    Gold amuletic figure of Thoth: the Ibis-headed Thoth is depicted in the round, wearing a long wig and short kilt with ornate belt. By artistic convention, as a male, he walks with left foot advanced. He holds out before him the 'wedjat' eye with its characteristic markings. The whole piece was presumably cast in a mould with all details, including those of minute signs on the 'wedjat', being incised subsequently. There is a loop behind the figure's shoulders for suspension.
